Prepare and submit Report on Physical Count of PPE for the current year 2019 to determine the actual physical count and condition of PPE at a given date including those unrecorded newly purchased and those which could not be accounted for; 

 Physical inventory taking of properties by type shall be conducted annually and Direct the Property Custodian to identify the unserviceable properties already subjected for disposal and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property.

We recommended that Management:

Prepare and submit Report on Physical Count of PPE for the current year 2019 to determine the actual physical count and condition of PPE at a given date including those unrecorded newly purchased and those which could not be accounted for;
Physical inventory taking of properties by type shall be conducted annually;
Prepare/maintain and update Property Cards and the PPE Ledger Cards by the Property Officer and the Municipal Accountant to facilitate reconciliation of the PPE Account.
Direct the Property Custodian to identify the unserviceable properties already subjected for disposal and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property.

We recommended that Management :

Intensify the immediate collections of the account dues from the officers and employees concerned;
Refrain or stop this malpractice to use government fund for the payment of personal loan amortization of the officers and employees;
Non-settlement and/or complete disregard to settle their accounts shall constitute a ground for the withholding of their salaries, and;
Failure of the officers and employees to settle their accounts, the auditor is compelled to issue Demand Letter and/or make a narrative report to apply the sanctions under the provisions of Art. 217 and 220 of the Revised Penal Code.

We recommended that Management:
Evaluate the reasonableness of the cellphone plans granted to the officials and employees;
Establish a managerial policy on the grant and use of cellular phones to officials and employees including the allowable amount chargeable to the municipality and limiting to one line per officer in order to avoid incurring excessive expenses as prohibited under COA Circular No. 2012-003; and Sec. 2 of PD 1445.

We recommended that Management:
Formulate a realistic and attainable work plans to ensure subprojects and activities are ready for implementation upon the release of the allocated funds;
Fast track the disbursement process in order to settle as soon as possible the due and demandable obligations and prevent accumulation of the unexpended fund balance.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of all inventory items and submit the corresponding RPCI and RPCPPE, semestral and annual, respectively;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate reconcile the existing discrepancy between the balances per book and RPCPPE;
Create the necessary committees in order to facilitate the proper disposal of identified unserviceable and obsolete properties.
Instruct the Municipal Account to effect the provision of depreciation on recognized Other Land Improvement and Infrastructure Asset accounts following the straight line method.

Require all accountable officers and employees to immediately liquidate their outstanding cash advances giving more emphasis to prior year outstanding advances by issuing Demand Letter;
Resort to the withholding of salaries of accountable officers and employees who still fail to settle their cash advances;
Exert extra effort to recover outstanding cash advances from AO who are no longer in the service or connected with the municipality.
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to strengthen internal control by strictly enforcing the provisions of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002.
We recommended and management agreed to strictly adhere to the provision of COA Circular No. 2009-0002 on granting of cash advances to LGU officials and employees.
